You can also use reduction. Personally i find a combination of [Stream.map()][1] and [Stream.reduce()][2] much easier to read, create and maintain.
```
BinaryOperator&lt;String&gt; stringMerger = (first, second) -&gt; first + &quot;, &quot; + second;
Pair&lt;String, String&gt; result = stream
        .map(p -&gt; Pair.of(p.left(), p.right().entrySet().stream().map(entry -&gt; entry.getKey() + &quot; &quot; + entry.getValue()).toList()))
        .map(p -&gt; Pair.of(p.left(), String.join(&quot;, &quot;, p.right()))) //you can also directly join the stream elements in the previous map() if you want
        .reduce((p1, p2) -&gt; p1.merge(p2, stringMerger, stringMerger))
        .map(pair -&gt; Pair.of(String.format(&quot;(%s)&quot;, pair.left()), pair.right() + &quot; add some desired text&quot;))
        .orElseThrow(() -&gt; new RuntimeException(&quot;Should not have happened&quot;));
System.out.println(result.left());
System.out.println(result.right());
```
Prints:
```
(fruits, vegetables, red meat, white meat)
yellow banana, red apple, yellow corn, red tomatoe, sheep mutton, cow beef, fish tuna, poultry chicken add some desired text
```
Pair is custom class for this example, since i don&#39;t know what the class you use looks like.
```
public record Pair&lt;L, R&gt;(L left, R right) {

  public static &lt;L, R&gt; Pair&lt;L, R&gt; of(L left, R right) {
    return new Pair&lt;&gt;(left, right);
  }

  public Pair&lt;L, R&gt; merge(Pair&lt;L, R&gt; other, BinaryOperator&lt;L&gt; leftMerger, BinaryOperator&lt;R&gt; rightMerger) {
    return of(leftMerger.apply(this.left, other.left), rightMerger.apply(this.right, other.right));
  }
}
```

  [1]: https://docs.oracle.com/javase/8/docs/api/java/util/stream/Stream.html#map-java.util.function.Function-
