So, initially there are some ... concerns.

`Canvas` already has `getWidth/Height` methods, overriding them in the way you are could have adverse and unexpected results.  As general rule, you should avoid overriding them.  Instead, override `getPreferredSize` and return the &quot;preferred&quot; sizing hints you&#39;d like used.

Use `getWidth/Height` to get the actual size of the component when you need to render to the `Canvas`&#39;s surface.

It &quot;could&quot; be a threading issue, in order to create a `BufferStrategy`, the `Canvas` will need to be realised on the screen (ie attached to a native peer), before this, `Canvas` won&#39;t be able to create a `BufferStrategy` (`getBufferStrategy` will always return `null`), so you could be in a race condition.

Your `start`/`stop` methods are a little dubious - what happens if the `thread` is already running?

So, I modified your code, attempting to address some of the issues above and implemented a rendering cycle based on the example from the [`BufferStrategy` JavaDocs](https://docs.oracle.com/en/java/javase/16/docs/api/java.desktop/java/awt/image/BufferStrategy.html) and had no issues getting it to work.

