You would need to cast to call a method from the `Equipment` class. Alternatively, you can use pattern matching for `instanceof`. Note, however, that this may likely be a symptom of improper design.

```java
if (i instanceof Equipment e) {
	e.getEquipmentVin();
} else if (i instanceof Product p) {
    p.someProductMethod();
}
```

If you have a list of Items (or some Item), you can only call Item methods on it. But you can cast it to Equipment (or Product) and then call the respective methods. Just be aware that casting an Item to Equipment while at runtime it is a Product (or something else) will give you a ClassCastException.

To work around that, first identify what you have before you cast:

    if (item instanceof Equipment) {
        Equipment e = (Equipment)item;
        e.getEquipmentVin();
    } else if (item instanceof Product) {
